					<description><![CDATA[<p>Emotional ads significantly out-perform bland, boring ads, but which emotions pack the biggest punch? Do happy, positive ads work better than ads that feed on negative emotions? Find out the top four click-driving emotions for ads in this data-backed post!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/11/09/emotional-ads">The 4 Emotions that Make the Best Emotional Ads [DATA]</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>After surveying a number of Paid Search Analysts here at WordStream, I was able to conclude the following: PPC can be really boring! I asked my peers to describe paid search in a few words. Their answers included: mundane, bland, dry, a numbers game, tedious, and mind-numbing.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="21d91904-7722-4cef-98ef-6db277e3da85" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-header.png" alt="Emotional Ads" width="726" height="363" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>It doesn‚Äôt have to be, though! Lots of experts love this field because actions drive results. It‚Äôs quantitative. As PPC specialists, we are often focused on the numbers ‚Äì impressions, bids, conversions, bounce rates. We forget to tap into the right side of our brains ‚Äì our intuition, emotion, and subjectivity. We find ourselves trapped in the left side of the brain with our logic, analytics, and objection. But the surprising truth is, our PPC campaigns can be wildly improved through the use of <em>emotional ads</em>.</p>
<p><strong>What happens if we take an entirely different approach to PPC and find out how emotions trigger the searcher to react?</strong> Are we more likely to click on an ad that is comical or one that instills shock? How about one that is emotionally driven with anger?</p>
<p>We dug into the data inside hundreds of client accounts to determine the <em>four key emotions</em> that are especially successful in leading to clicks and conversions. Over the past few months, I‚Äôve tested ad copy that instilled each of these four emotional drivers across various sectors and industries ‚Äì really running the gamut from medical practices to online clothing retailers to personal disability lawyers. My findings have been intriguing, and I was able to draw some very obvious trends from the testing.</p>
<p>In this blog post, I‚Äôll show you why these four emotions ‚Äì <strong>anger, disgust, affirmation, and fear</strong> ‚Äì work so well to drive PPC results, as well as how to put them to work in ads that get crazy-high engagement, with lots of real-life examples.</p>
<p>Before we get into the fun stuff, let me tell you exactly why you need emotional ads.</p>
<h2>Quality Score and the Power of High Click-Through Rates</h2>
<p>Google has this crazy algorithm called <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/adwords-quality-score">Quality Score</a>. As you‚Äôve heard, Quality Score is a secret concoction of past performance, ad copy relevance, overall account quality, landing page relevancy, keyword relevancy, and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2010/04/26/good-click-through-rate">click-through rate</a>. But here‚Äôs the hack ‚Äì click-through rate is the <strong>single most powerful thing</strong> you can focus on when trying to improve your Quality Score.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="59af272f-7e79-4795-8ccb-0f731bc13bc8" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-quality-score-1.png" alt="Emotional ads Quality Score" width="583" height="317" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2013/10/28/adwords-impression-share">Impression share</a> goes up or down 9% for every 1 point increase or decrease in Quality Score. So basically if you don‚Äôt have a good QS, your ads won‚Äôt show up on the SERP much. What‚Äôs the point in creating ads no one is going to see?</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="0570c831-9763-4460-9e71-60c6551333f1" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-impression-share.png" alt="Emotional ads Impression Share" width="464" height="310" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>You also need a good Quality Score so you can get your clicks for as cheap as possible. Having a score of 10 discounts your cost per click by 50% on average. By having a lower Quality Score, you‚Äôre going to be majorly overpaying for your clicks ‚Äì sometimes even 400% higher than face value.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="40553880-3270-4832-84e1-89bc88002606" data-langcode="en">
<article><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/how-quality-score-impacts-cost-per-click-google-ads.png" alt="how quality score impacts cost per click" width="720" height="523" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-61091" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/how-quality-score-impacts-cost-per-click-google-ads.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/how-quality-score-impacts-cost-per-click-google-ads-480x357.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></article>
</div>
<p>Lots of people think that dynamic keyword insertion produces the best ads. This is an incorrect assumption. Dynamic keyword insertion <em>does</em> work‚Ä¶</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="48947a35-e983-404d-8c00-a9b4a3e9f3c3" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-dynamic-keyword-insertion.png" alt="Emotional ads dynamic keyword insertion" width="401" height="304" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>But dynamic keyword insertion doesn‚Äôt put your ad into the top 1% ‚Äì the ads that <em>really</em> grab people‚Äôs attention and earn <a href="/blog/ws/2014/02/11/average-click-through-rate">super high CTRs</a>. Emotions do that!</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="227f7425-f4ac-43a9-a21d-222667200191" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-dynamic-keyword-insertion-relative.png" alt="Emotional ads relative dynamic keyword insertion" width="392" height="310" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>So to recap why we need good emotional ads‚Ä¶. Good ads lead to a higher click-through rates which earn you a higher Quality Score and thus‚Ä¶ cheaper clicks.</p>
<h2>Why Emotional Ads Perform So Well</h2>
<p>Now let‚Äôs talk science for a hot second. There‚Äôs two main parts of the brain that drive our actions ‚Äì the frontal lobe and the limbic system. The frontal lobe is pictured below in pink. This is the ‚Äúlogical brain,‚Äù and it is associated with our reasoning, planning, parts of speech, movement, and problem solving. The limbic system is the ‚Äúemotional brain.‚Äù This is where our intuition, subjectivity, and emotions take the reins.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="7c38bab9-46b5-4e12-93fc-e186b921a237" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-logic-vs-emotion-1.png" alt="Emotional ads logic vs emotion" width="532" height="345" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Think about any commercial that you deem entertaining. I have an obsession with pretty much any Budweiser Clydesdale or puppy commercial. Why? Because I love animals and they pull at my heart strings. They run viewers through the whole gamut of emotions from sadness to fear to happiness. Now I don‚Äôt even like Budweiser (we all know Bud makes less than subpar beer), but we feel a strong affiliation with the brand because they make these awesome, emotionally charged commercials. <strong>Budweiser isn‚Äôt selling the beer. They‚Äôre selling what connotations you have with the beer. </strong></p>
<p>It‚Äôs not just TV commercials that make use of emotions. Emotionally driven ads are prominent in all other forms of advertising ‚Äì from billboards to radio and even digital marketing ‚Äì like <a href="/blog/ws/2015/11/05/content-marketing-for-ppc">content marketing</a> and social media. But somehow PPC missed the boat!</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="32d599af-3946-4ee5-b975-6ec5ab5d02e6" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-auto-insurance-serp.png" alt="Emotional ads auto insurance SERP" width="498" height="297" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>I recently Googled ‚Äúauto insurance‚Äù and came up with the above ads. These ads were AWFUL. They all said the same thing. Bad credit accepted. No money down. Call today. Google gives advertisers all the same old tips and best practices for ad copy creation: Include prices, offer a promotion, use a call to action‚Ä¶ If we all do the same thing then our ads are all going to mirror one another. No one‚Äôs ad stands out!</p>
<p>So forget the generic ads ‚Äì let‚Äôs create some emotionally charged ads that will get your users clicking!</p>
<h2>Helen‚Äôs Foolproof Process for Creating Emotional Ads</h2>
<p>Here are the steps I follow to write high-performing emotional ads for my clients:</p>
<p><strong>Step 1</strong> ‚Äì Who is your customer? Is she a working mother? A hippie yoga kale eater? A high society trust fund baby?</p>
<p><strong>Step 2</strong> ‚Äì What persona do you want to take on in relation to your target market? Bearer of bad news? Hero/Villain dynamic? The comedian? The feel good friend?</p>
<p><strong>Step 3</strong> ‚Äì Write emotionally charged ads from the standpoint of the chosen persona.</p>
<p>So without further ado ‚Äì let‚Äôs dig into the top 4 emotions that make people click and convert like BONKERS!</p>
<p><em><a href="/blog/ws/2021/05/03/emotional-marketing-copy">Need help with emotional marketing copy? We&#8217;ve got you covered.</a></em></p>
<h2>Top Emotions for Ad Copy Domination #4 ‚Äì ANGER</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="b806b9d4-6e7c-4d72-a63a-22454c03fef1" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-anger.png" alt="Emotional ads anger" width="264" height="271" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Let‚Äôs write an ad from a divorce lawyer‚Äôs standpoint using my coveted process. Who‚Äôs the customer? A pissed off woman. What persona do we want to play on? The hero/villain dynamic. Here‚Äôs an ad that capitalizes on the searcher‚Äôs feelings:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="949edc64-9258-4a3b-bbfa-ddbd2212c650" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-divorce-lawyer-ad.png" alt="Emotional ads divorce lawyer ad" width="530" height="154" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Here‚Äôs a real-life example. We‚Äôve all heard the commercials on daytime TV in between Jerry Springer and Judge Judy. I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôll ever forget the JG Wentworth ad: IT‚ÄôS MY MONEY AND I WANT IT NOW! 877-CASH NOW!</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="31b9fde2-d815-45a5-91ac-eef137b5b75f" data-langcode="en">
