</article>
</div>
<h2>Top Emotions for Ad Copy Domination #1 ‚Äì FEAR</h2>
<p>I have a client who specializes in breast cancer screening services. I wanted this client to succeed, not only for the sake of my bonus, but because it‚Äôs something I really care about. This is the ad they were running when they came onboard as a client:</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="6cbfaf5f-9b6c-4abb-891b-50cf861c77db" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-fear-ad.png" alt="Emotional ads fear" width="434" height="115" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><strong>¬†</strong>This ad isn‚Äôt compelling because we‚Äôve all heard this saying (‚Äúearly detection saves lives‚Äù) so many times. This saying doesn‚Äôt get a woman to take action anymore, because it‚Äôs become too much of a clich√©. I paused this ad and replaced it with 2 new ones, shown below.</p>
<p><strong>POSITIVITY</strong></p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="6bbb8d90-25cb-4642-9c0e-1d025941921d" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-positivity-ad.png" alt="Emotional ads positivity ad" width="437" height="160" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><strong>NEGATIVITY </strong></p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="d0f18fd2-05b1-49da-b61c-30ec2955be73" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-negativity-ad-1.png" alt="Emotional ads negativity ad" width="407" height="142" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>This first new ad had a positive twist in the language. It was stronger than the old ad, with more conviction, but still weak. For the next version of the ad, I thought about who my target customer was ‚Äì likely a frightened woman, with kids, a husband, and responsibilities. She was searching something along the lines of ‚Äúbreast cancer symptoms,‚Äù so more likely than not she was thinking she might have breast cancer. This is where I knew we had to catch her.</p>
<p>The persona we took on was the ‚Äúbearer of bad news.‚Äù This second ad is by no means a feel-good ad. It‚Äôs definitely not conventional, but it is memorable and got women in to get screened. In telling a woman this fact, we purposefully meant to scare her ‚Äì and the negative ad produced <strong>125% more appointments</strong> booked, compared to the <a href="/blog/ws/2017/08/08/positive-vs-negative-ads">positive ad</a>.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="f9814808-3629-48d0-8d8e-4e0a53995ebf" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-negative-vs-positive.png" alt="Emotional ads impact of negative vs positive" width="528" height="295" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Even more striking was that the negative ad produced <strong>170% more phone calls</strong>, compared to the positive ad. This makes a lot of sense. The woman is having an emergency ‚Äì so she‚Äôs more likely to <a href="/blog/ws/2015/04/22/call-tracking-industries">take immediate action and to call</a> and book an appointment ‚Äì rather than filling out a more passive call back form.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="4eae98ad-1f14-464c-8b44-b48459fecf8a" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/emotional-ads-positive-vs-negative.png" alt="Emotional ads impact of positive vs negative" width="525" height="294" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>So for the love of paid search ‚Äì go write some creative new ads (with <a href="/blog/ws/2021/01/13/best-words-and-phrases-for-marketing">emotional words, phrases</a>, and imagery), and I guarantee you that in a couple of months you‚Äôll see a dramatic change in your ad performance. Remember ‚Äì small changes equate to small results and big changes equate to big results. Making a small change, like using dynamic keyword insertion, will give you a small increase in click through rate. Writing completely new emotional ads that make your searchers feel something will lead to big changes! Be the mad scientist and prey upon people‚Äôs emotions. Don‚Äôt be afraid to test big, crazy things. When you find something that works, it‚Äôs like finding gold!</p>
<p>Larry Kim always uses this silly analogy ‚Äì ‚ÄúBe the unicorn in a sea of donkeys.‚Äù</p>
